primitive_props.translation: This document is an agreement on the non-disclosure of confidential information (two-way).
primitive_props.evidence: Title: "AGREEMENT ON THE NON-DISCLOSURE OF CONFIDENTIAL INFORMATION (TWO-WAY)"
primitive_props.explanation: Atomic classification of the document; no logical connective.

primitive_props.translation: The agreement has an effective date (the day of 200_).
primitive_props.evidence: Opening paragraph: "This Agreement is made with an effective date of the day of 200_"
primitive_props.explanation: Single factual/date term; not decomposable into smaller propositions.

primitive_props.translation: The University of Bristol is a party to the agreement.
primitive_props.evidence: Opening paragraph: "between The University of Bristol ... and ... (the \"Parties\")"

primitive_props.translation: The other signatory organization/person is a party to the agreement.
primitive_props.evidence: Opening paragraph: "between The University of Bristol ... and __________ ... (the \"Parties\")"

primitive_props.translation: The purpose of the agreement is to regulate the exchange of confidential information.
primitive_props.evidence: Purpose paragraph: "THE PURPOSE ... is to regulate the exchange ... of confidential information"
primitive_props.explanation: Single stated purpose component; atomic as one purpose-claim.

primitive_props.translation: The purpose of the agreement is to regulate the subsequent treatment of confidential information.
primitive_props.evidence: Purpose paragraph: "... exchange and subsequent treatment of confidential information"
primitive_props.explanation: Single stated purpose component; atomic as one purpose-claim.

primitive_props.translation: The purpose is to protect the proper interests of the disclosing party while the information is in the possession or control of the receiving party.
primitive_props.evidence: Purpose paragraph: "... so as to protect the proper interests ... whilst ... in the possession or control of the receiving party"
primitive_props.explanation: Single protective-purpose statement; not a logical combination of separate obligations.

primitive_props.translation: Confidential information includes proprietary materials.
primitive_props.evidence: Definition paragraph: "confidential information includes proprietary materials"

primitive_props.translation: Confidential information includes specifications, drawings, designs, computer software, and knowhow.
primitive_props.evidence: Definition paragraph: "including without limitation specifications, drawings, designs, computer software and knowhow"
primitive_props.explanation: Single definitional inclusion statement (a listed set); atomic at the level of the contract definition.

primitive_props.translation: The receiving party affords disclosed confidential information the same degree of protection as it affords its own information.
primitive_props.evidence: Purpose paragraph: "In general the receiving party must afford ... the same degree of protection as it would afford its own."
primitive_props.explanation: Single protection-standard requirement; atomic though it compares protection levels.

primitive_props.translation: The disclosure of confidential information is for the specific purpose of evaluating technology in the described field.
primitive_props.evidence: Clause 1: "The disclosure of confidential information is for the specific purpose of evaluating technology..."

primitive_props.translation: Disclosures are between the University of Bristol and the other party.
primitive_props.evidence: Clause 1: "... will normally be between ... the University of Bristol and ..."
primitive_props.explanation: Single statement about who disclosures occur between; atomic (frequency/hedge handled in constraints).

primitive_props.translation: Some documents or materials are provided on loan for the stated purposes.
primitive_props.evidence: Clause 1: "Any specific documents or materials which are necessarily provided on loan..."
primitive_props.explanation: Single existence/possibility of loaned materials; atomic.

primitive_props.translation: Loaned documents or materials are specified in a schedule to the agreement.
primitive_props.evidence: Clause 1: "... will be specified in a schedule to this Agreement"

primitive_props.translation: The disclosing party requests the return of provided documents or materials.
primitive_props.evidence: Clause 1: "... the receiving party will return these ... to the disclosing party on request."
primitive_props.explanation: Single trigger condition (a request is made); atomic.

primitive_props.translation: The receiving party returns provided documents or materials to the disclosing party.
primitive_props.evidence: Clause 1: "... the receiving party will return these ... to the disclosing party"

primitive_props.translation: The parties mark or otherwise designate confidential information to indicate it is imparted in confidence.
primitive_props.evidence: Clause 2: "The parties will mark or otherwise designate confidential information..."

primitive_props.translation: The information item is disclosed in connection with this agreement.
primitive_props.evidence: Clause 3: "... confidential information ... which is disclosed in connection with this Agreement"
primitive_props.explanation: Single condition about the information item; atomic.

primitive_props.translation: The confidentiality obligations of the agreement apply to the information item.
primitive_props.evidence: Clause 4: "the obligations herein undertaken will not apply to ..." (implies a notion of when obligations apply)
primitive_props.explanation: A meta-status proposition needed to model the contract’s exceptions; atomic as a single applicability flag.

primitive_props.translation: The receiving party takes proper and reasonable measures to maintain confidentiality of the information.
primitive_props.evidence: Clause 3(a): "it will take all proper and reasonable measures..."

primitive_props.translation: The receiving party uses the information for a commercial purpose or for manufacture.
primitive_props.evidence: Clause 3(b): "... not use the information for any commercial purpose or manufacture ..."

primitive_props.translation: The receiving party has obtained a written licence or other agreement from the disclosing party.
primitive_props.evidence: Clause 3(b): "... without obtaining a written licence or other agreement from the disclosing party"

primitive_props.translation: The receiving party discloses the information to a third party.
primitive_props.evidence: Clause 3(c): "it will not disclose the information to any third party..."

primitive_props.translation: The receiving party has written permission from the disclosing party to disclose to a third party.
primitive_props.evidence: Clause 3(c): "... without written permission"

primitive_props.translation: The receiving party discloses the information to employees other than those previously authorized.
primitive_props.evidence: Clause 3(d): "... will not disclose ... to employees other than those above except ..."

primitive_props.translation: Disclosure to such other employees is necessary to fulfil the agreement’s stated purposes.
primitive_props.evidence: Clause 3(d): "... except to the extent necessary to fulfil the purposes set out above"

primitive_props.translation: Those other employees are made aware of the confidential nature of the information and the conditions of disclosure.
primitive_props.evidence: Clause 3(d): "... will be made aware of the confidential nature ... and the conditions ..."

primitive_props.translation: The receiving party makes a copy of, or an abstract of, the information.
primitive_props.evidence: Clause 3(e): "... will not make any copy of or abstract of the information..."

primitive_props.translation: The receiving party has specific written permission from the disclosing party to copy or abstract the information.
primitive_props.evidence: Clause 3(e): "... without specific written permission from the disclosing party"

primitive_props.translation: The receiving party acknowledges the source organization of the information.
primitive_props.evidence: Clause 3(f): "it will acknowledge the source..."

primitive_props.translation: The receiving party marks "Confidential" on any drawing, document, or software incorporating the information.
primitive_props.evidence: Clause 3(f): "... will mark \"Confidential\", any drawing, document or software incorporating the information."

primitive_props.translation: There is no transfer of ownership to the receiving party of any drawings, documents, or software under the agreement.
primitive_props.evidence: Clause 4: "there is no explicit or implied transfer of ownership to the receiving party..."

primitive_props.translation: There is no transfer of copyright to the receiving party in those drawings, documents, or software under the agreement.
primitive_props.evidence: Clause 4: "... or the copyright subsisting in them."

primitive_props.translation: The receiving party owns the drawings, documents, or software.
primitive_props.evidence: Clause 4 discusses ownership transfer (used to model the contrary state).
primitive_props.explanation: Single ownership status (the opposite of the stated contract position); atomic.

primitive_props.translation: The receiving party owns the copyright in the drawings, documents, or software.
primitive_props.evidence: Clause 4 discusses copyright transfer (used to model the contrary state).
primitive_props.explanation: Single copyright ownership status (the opposite of the stated contract position); atomic.

primitive_props.translation: The information is in the public domain at the time of disclosure.
primitive_props.evidence: Clause 4(a): "information which at the time of disclosure is in the public domain"

primitive_props.translation: After disclosure, the information becomes part of the public domain through no fault of the recipient.
primitive_props.evidence: Clause 4(a): "... or which after disclosure becomes part of the public domain through no fault of the recipient"

primitive_props.translation: The recipient can show the information was in its possession at the time of disclosure.
primitive_props.evidence: Clause 4(b): "... can show was in its possession at the time of disclosure"

primitive_props.translation: The recipient independently developed the information and did not acquire it from the disclosing party.
primitive_props.evidence: Clause 4(b): "... independently developed ... and was not acquired ... from the disclosing party"
primitive_props.explanation: Single exception condition expressed as one status; treated atomically at contract granularity.

primitive_props.translation: The disclosing party makes the information public.
primitive_props.evidence: Clause 4(c): "information which is made public ... by the disclosing party"

primitive_props.translation: Others make the information public with the disclosing party's permission.
primitive_props.evidence: Clause 4(c): "... or by others with the permission of the disclosing party"

primitive_props.translation: The receiving party receives the information from a third party without similar restriction and without breach of this agreement.
primitive_props.evidence: Clause 4(d): "information which is received ... from a third party without similar restriction and without breach of this Agreement"

primitive_props.translation: The information is required to be disclosed by legal process, law, or regulatory authority.
primitive_props.evidence: Clause 4(e): "information which is required to be disclosed by legal process, law or regulatory authority"

primitive_props.translation: A party communicates or divulges to third parties confidential information received from the other party during/after discussions and within ten years from the effective date.
primitive_props.evidence: Clause 5: "... not to communicate or to divulge to third parties confidential information received from the other party... for a period of ten (10) years"
primitive_props.explanation: Single action/event proposition capturing the prohibited conduct; atomic.

primitive_props.translation: The agreement is construed and enforced in accordance with English law.
primitive_props.evidence: Clause 6: "This Agreement is to be construed and enforced in accordance with English Law"

primitive_props.translation: The agreement is subject to the exclusive jurisdiction of the English courts.
primitive_props.evidence: Clause 6: "... subject to the exclusive jurisdiction of the English courts"

primitive_props.translation: A party seeks interim relief in a court of competent jurisdiction.
primitive_props.evidence: Clause 6: "... shall not prevent a party from seeking interim relief in any court of competent jurisdiction."

primitive_props.translation: The information item is confidential information for purposes of this agreement.
primitive_props.evidence: Definition paragraph: "For the purposes of this Agreement the term confidential information includes ..."
primitive_props.explanation: A classification proposition needed to connect definitional content to obligations; atomic.

hard_constraints.translation: This two-way NDA exists, has an effective date, and has the University of Bristol and the other signatory as parties.
hard_constraints.reasoning: These are direct assertions establishing the contract and the parties.

hard_constraints.translation: The agreement’s purpose is to regulate exchange and subsequent treatment of confidential information and protect the disclosing party’s interests while in the receiver’s control.
Confidential information includes proprietary materials and related information (e.g., specifications, drawings, designs, software, knowhow).
If documents/materials are provided on loan, they are specified in a schedule to the agreement.
hard_constraints.evidence: Clause 1: "... provided on loan ... will be specified in a schedule"
hard_constraints.reasoning: Clause 1 makes scheduling a requirement tied to the loan condition.

hard_constraints.translation: If the disclosing party requests return, the receiving party returns the provided documents/materials.
hard_constraints.reasoning: A direct conditional obligation triggered by a request.

hard_constraints.translation: The parties mark/designate confidential information as imparted in confidence.
hard_constraints.evidence: Clause 2: "The parties will mark or otherwise designate confidential information..."
hard_constraints.reasoning: "Will" in a contract is a binding term; the marking/designation is required.

hard_constraints.translation: If any exception in Clause 4 holds (public domain, prior possession, independent development, made public, third-party source without restriction, or required by law), then the agreement’s confidentiality obligations do not apply to that information.
hard_constraints.evidence: Clause 4: "PROVIDED that the obligations herein undertaken will not apply to: (a)-(e)"
hard_constraints.reasoning: Clause 4 explicitly carves out situations where confidentiality obligations are inapplicable.

hard_constraints.translation: If information is disclosed in connection with the agreement and no Clause 4 exception holds, then the confidentiality obligations apply to that information.
hard_constraints.evidence: Clause 3 (obligations for info disclosed in connection) + Clause 4 (exceptions)
hard_constraints.reasoning: Combines Clause 3’s baseline application with Clause 4’s explicit carve-outs to define when obligations apply.

hard_constraints.translation: If the confidentiality obligations apply, the receiving party takes proper and reasonable measures to maintain confidentiality.
hard_constraints.reasoning: Clause 3 conditions are binding when obligations apply.

hard_constraints.translation: If the confidentiality obligations apply, the receiving party does not use the information commercially/manufacture unless it has a written licence/other agreement from the disclosing party.
hard_constraints.reasoning: Direct prohibition with an explicit permission condition; modeled as (not use) or (licence).

hard_constraints.translation: If the confidentiality obligations apply, the receiving party does not disclose to third parties unless it has written permission.
hard_constraints.reasoning: Direct prohibition with an explicit permission condition; modeled as (not disclose) or (permission).

hard_constraints.translation: If the confidentiality obligations apply, the receiving party does not disclose to other (non-authorized) employees unless necessary to fulfil the purposes.
hard_constraints.evidence: Clause 3(d): "... except to the extent necessary to fulfil the purposes..."
hard_constraints.reasoning: Clause 3(d) allows disclosure only under a necessity condition.

hard_constraints.translation: If the confidentiality obligations apply and the receiving party discloses to such other employees, those employees are made aware of the confidential nature and disclosure conditions.
hard_constraints.evidence: Clause 3(d): "... and all such other employees ... will be made aware..."
hard_constraints.reasoning: Clause 3(d) imposes an additional mandatory condition whenever that employee disclosure happens.

hard_constraints.translation: If the confidentiality obligations apply, the receiving party does not copy/abstract unless it has specific written permission.
hard_constraints.reasoning: Direct prohibition with an explicit permission condition; modeled as (not copy) or (permission).

hard_constraints.translation: If the confidentiality obligations apply, the receiving party acknowledges the source and marks "Confidential" on drawings/documents/software incorporating the information.
hard_constraints.reasoning: Clause 3(f) imposes affirmative obligations on acknowledgement and marking.

hard_constraints.translation: If there is no transfer of ownership under the agreement, then the receiving party does not own the drawings/documents/software by virtue of this agreement.
hard_constraints.evidence: Clause 4: "no explicit or implied transfer of ownership"
hard_constraints.reasoning: Semantic/legal consequence: "no transfer of ownership" contradicts receiver ownership arising from the agreement.

hard_constraints.translation: If there is no transfer of copyright under the agreement, then the receiving party does not own the copyright by virtue of this agreement.
hard_constraints.evidence: Clause 4: "... or the copyright subsisting in them"
hard_constraints.reasoning: Semantic/legal consequence: "no transfer of copyright" contradicts receiver copyright ownership arising from the agreement.

hard_constraints.translation: If the confidentiality obligations apply, a party does not communicate/divulge confidential information received from the other party to third parties during/after discussions and within ten years from the effective date.
hard_constraints.evidence: Clause 5: "Both parties agree ... not to communicate or to divulge to third parties ... for a period of ten (10) years"
hard_constraints.reasoning: Clause 5 is a binding non-disclosure obligation; Clause 4 exceptions are captured by conditioning on P_19 (obligations apply).

hard_constraints.translation: The agreement is governed by English law, is under exclusive English court jurisdiction, and parties may still seek interim relief in any competent court.
hard_constraints.evidence: Clause 6: governing law + exclusive jurisdiction + interim relief carve-out
hard_constraints.reasoning: All three are explicit contract terms; the text states they coexist.

soft_constraints.translation: If confidentiality obligations apply, the receiving party affords confidential information the same degree of protection as its own information.
soft_constraints.evidence: Purpose paragraph: "In general the receiving party must afford ... the same degree of protection..."
soft_constraints.reasoning: The hedge phrase "In general" indicates defeasibility; the core rule is stated but not absolute.

soft_constraints.translation: Disclosures are between the University of Bristol and the other party.
soft_constraints.reasoning: The hedge word "normally" indicates this is typical rather than guaranteed.

soft_constraints.translation: If the parties mark/designate information as imparted in confidence, then the information is confidential information for purposes of the agreement.
soft_constraints.evidence: Clause 2 (mark/designate to show it is imparted in confidence) + definition section
soft_constraints.reasoning: Common-sense/legal practice: marking as confidential is strong evidence it is treated as confidential under the agreement, but edge cases exist (e.g., mistaken marking).

soft_constraints.translation: If something is a proprietary material (as described), then it is confidential information under the agreement.
soft_constraints.evidence: Definition paragraph: "confidential information includes proprietary materials"
soft_constraints.reasoning: This is definitional, but in practical settings classification disputes can occur; treated as soft to reflect possible interpretation/contestability while staying aligned with the definition.
